cs.CL, cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.NE

This paper deals with natural language processing and machine learning techniques to resolve toponyms, which are location mentions in a document. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also involves information retrieval techniques to estimate the geographic scope of documents, which suggests cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as another possible category. The paper proposes an unsupervised model that leverages connections between nearby place names, which falls under the category of unsupervised learning and clustering, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a likely category as well. The paper also involves building a model that finds the most coherent resolution by exploring the interactions between multiple interpretations of mentions and the relationships between different toponyms in a document, which suggests cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) as another possible category. Finally, the paper proposes a method that outperforms the state-of-the-art supervised method when the test data has 40% or more toponyms that are not seen in the training data, which suggests cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) as another possible category.
